instruction:
I'm trying to make HTTP requests in Node.js using the built-in `http` module, but I'm having trouble handling errors and different HTTP status codes effectively in a production-like environment. My current code only logs the response data and has basic error handling. 

Here's a simplified version:

```typescript
import http from 'http';

const options = {
  hostname: 'example.com',
  port: 80,
  path: '/api/users',
  method: 'GET'
};

const req = http.request(options, (res) => {
  let data = '';
  res.on('data', (chunk) => {
    data += chunk;
  });
  res.on('end', () => {
    console.log('Response data:', data);
  });
});

req.on('error', (e) => {
  console.error('Error:', e);
});

req.end();

```

How can I make this more robust, specifically handling different status codes (like 400, 500) and network errors, and providing more informative error messages?  I also want to ensure my code is type-safe and follows best practices for a production setting.

files.content:
```typescript
import http, { IncomingMessage, RequestOptions } from 'http';

export interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T | null;
  error: Error | null;
  statusCode: number | null;
}

export async function makeRequest<T>(options: RequestOptions): Promise<ApiResponse<T>> {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const req = http.request(options, (res: IncomingMessage) => {
      let data = '';
      res.on('data', (chunk) => {
        data += chunk;
      });

      res.on('end', () => {
        try {
          const parsedData: T = JSON.parse(data);
          resolve({ data: parsedData, error: null, statusCode: res.statusCode });
        } catch (error) {
          resolve({ data: null, error: error as Error, statusCode: res.statusCode });
        }
      });

      res.on('error', (error) => {
        resolve({ data: null, error: error, statusCode: res.statusCode });
      });
    });

    req.on('error', (error) => {
      resolve({ data: null, error: error, statusCode: null });
    });
    req.end();
  });
}

```

