chosen:
CSS Modules allow you to write CSS in a modular fashion, where each class name is scoped locally by default. This prevents naming conflicts and makes styles easier to manage. You import the CSS file as a module in your JavaScript files.

In your code, you should change how you reference the styles in your component:

Example of CSS Modules usage:

```css
/* styles.module.css */
.button {
  background-color: green;
  color: white;
  padding: 10px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  cursor: pointer;
}
```

```javascript
import styles from './styles.module.css';

const App: React.FC = () => <button className={styles.button}>Click Me</button>;
```

In this example, the CSS is written in 'styles.module.css', and the styles are imported as a module in the JavaScript file. The 'className' attribute is set to 'styles.button', which applies the locally scoped styles to the button component.

